# âš¡ gk6 â€“ Generate k6 Load Tests from Postman Collections

[![License: MIT](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-yellow.svg)](/LICENSE)
[![Python](https://img.shields.io/badge/Python-3.8%2B-blue)](https://www.python.org/)
[![Docs](https://img.shields.io/badge/Docs-GitHub%20Pages-blue)](https://gopikrishna4595.github.io/gk6/)

**gk6** is a Python CLI tool that converts Postman collections into dynamic [k6](https://k6.io) performance testing scripts â€” with support for chaining variables, environment parsing, automated metrics, and HTML reporting. Built to automate what you shouldnâ€™t have to hand-code.

---

## ðŸŽ¯ Why gk6?

If you use Postman for API testing and k6 for performance testing, this tool connects the dots:

- âœ… No need to rewrite each request manually
- ðŸ” It respects your chaining logic (`pm.environment.set`)
- ðŸŒ Supports environments and headers out of the box
- ðŸ“Š Visibility with built-in checks and trend metrics

---

## âœ… Features

- âœ… Converts any Postman Collection to a runnable k6 script
- âœ… Supports `GET`, `POST`, `PUT`, `DELETE` methods
- ðŸ”„ Recognizes and converts environment variables (`{{var}}`)
- ðŸ” Detects request chaining via `pm.environment.set()`
- ðŸ“Š Auto-generates `Trend` metrics and `check()` assertions
- ðŸ–¥ CLI-friendly with `argparse`
- ðŸ“„ Optional `.env` and HTML summary output with `k6-reporter`

---

## ðŸ§± Limitations

* â— Currently supports only `pm.environment.set()` for chaining â€” `pm.variables.set()` is not yet handled.
* âš ï¸ Does not parse pre-request scripts or tests written in advanced Postman JavaScript.
* ðŸ”’ Sensitive auth flows (e.g., OAuth2 with token rotation) require manual setup.
* ðŸ“„ HTML reporting requires `k6-reporter` installed and configured separately.
* ðŸ“¦ Limited to JSON-based Postman collections (v2.1+).

---

## ðŸš€ Quick Start

### 1. Install

No extra packages needed â€” just Python 3.8+ and [k6](https://k6.io/docs/getting-started/installation)

```bash
pip install poetry
poetry install
```

### 2. Run the CLI

```bash
poetry run gk6 --help
```

Convert a Postman collection and environment:

```bash
poetry run gk6 convert --collection postman.json --env environment.json
```

